{"title_page": "Lesley Garrett", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name           = Lesley Garrett<br><small>[[Order of the British Empire|CBE]]</small>\n| alias          = \n| background     = solo_singer\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| birth_name     = \n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1955|4|10}}\n| birth_place    = [[Thorne, South Yorkshire|Thorne]], [[Doncaster]], [[South Yorkshire]], England\n| occupation     = {{hlist|Singer\u2013songwriter|musician|broadcaster|[[Infotainment|media personality]]}}\n| genre          = Classical, [[crossover music|classical-crossover]]\n| years_active   = 1979\u2013present\n| label          = [[Decca Records|Decca]]<br>[[Universal Classics and Jazz]]<br>[[Universal Music International]]\n| website        = [http://www.lesleygarrett.co.uk/ Official site]\n}}\n\n'''Lesley Garrett''', [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] (born 10 April 1955) is an English [[soprano singer]], musician, broadcaster and media personality.  She is noted for being at home in opera and \"[[crossover music]]\".<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/1734956.stm |title=UK &#124; Lesley Garrett: Doncaster's own diva |publisher=BBC News |date=31 December 2001 |accessdate=10 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nGarrett was born in the town of [[Thorne, South Yorkshire|Thorne]], near Doncaster, South Yorkshire into a musical family. She attended Thorne Fieldside Infant and Junior Schools and [[Thorne Grammar School]], where she performed in school plays and musicals and passed 10 [[GCE Ordinary Level|O-levels]] and an [[GCE Advanced Level|A-level]] in music.<ref>''[[Daily Mail]]'' Weekend Interview. 12 May 2012, p6</ref> As she grew up she inherited her family's love of music. Her grandfather Colin Wall was a classical pianist; her father Derek worked as a railway signalman and then as a schoolteacher at Hatfield Woodhouse Primary School, eventually going on to become a headmaster. They lived nearby just south of the village; her mother Margaret (n\u00e9e Wall) was a talented singing seamstress and became the school secretary at Lesley's primary school. She has two sisters, Jill and Kay, one step-sister, Louise, and two step-brothers named Robert and Nicholas. At the age of 17 Garrett washed dishes at the officers' mess at nearby [[RAF Lindholme]] as a summer job.<ref name=\"Dishes\">{{cite web|author=Liz Phillips |url=http://www.thisismoney.co.uk/celebrity/article.html?in_article_id=421297&in_page_id=181 |title=Lesley Garrett: My money |publisher=This is Money |date=13 June 2007 |accessdate=10 August 2014}}</ref> While a student at the [[Royal Academy of Music]] she worked as a life model, something of which she is still proud.<ref>{{cite web |last=Paton |first=Maureen |url=http://mygetupandgo.co.uk/2012/06/this-life-lesley-garrett/ |title=This LIfe, Lesley Garrett &#124; Get up and go |publisher=Mygetupandgo.co.uk |date=3 June 2012 |accessdate=10 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140730151143/http://mygetupandgo.co.uk/2012/06/this-life-lesley-garrett/ |archivedate=30 July 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Music==\nGarrett has had an extensive music career. A graduate of the [[Royal Academy of Music]] and an alumna of the prestigious [[National Opera Studio]], she won the Decca Prize of the [[Kathleen Ferrier Award]] in 1979, thereby launching her career.<ref>{{cite web\n|url = http://www.ferrierawards.org.uk/main/winners.asp\n|title = The Kathleen Ferrier Awards \u2013 Winners\n|accessdate = 6 March 2008}}</ref> Her professional debut, in 1979, was as Amor in ''[[Orontea]]'' at the music festival in [[Batignano]]. She subsequently sang, in 1980, Alice in ''[[Le comte Ory]]'' at the [[London Coliseum]] and Dorinda in ''[[Orlando (opera)|Orlando]]'' at the [[Wexford Festival]], in 1981, also at Wexford, the title role in ''[[Zaide]]'', in 1982 Sophie in ''[[Werther]]'' with [[Opera North]] and in 1984 Damigella in ''[[L'incoronazione di Poppea]]'' at [[Glyndebourne Festival Opera|Glyndebourne]].<ref>{{cite book| last = Adam| first = Nicky (ed)| year = 1993| title = Who's Who in British Opera| publisher = Scolar Press| location = Aldershot| page = [https://archive.org/details/whoswhoinbritish0000adam/page/98 98]| isbn = 0-859-67894-6| url = https://archive.org/details/whoswhoinbritish0000adam/page/98}}</ref> From 1984, as principal soprano at [[English National Opera]], she became well known for her performances in productions of the operas ''[[Serse]]'', ''[[The Marriage of Figaro|Le Nozze di Figaro]]'', ''[[Cos\u00ec fan tutte]]'' ''[[Die Fledermaus]]''<ref name=\"bbc\" /> and ''[[The Mikado]]''.<ref>Rahim, Sameer. [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/opera/9841816/The-opera-novice-The-Mikado-by-Gilbert-and-Sullivan.html \"The opera novice: ''The Mikado'' by Gilbert & Sullivan\"], ''The Telegraph'', 1 February 2013</ref>\n\nGarrett has performed across the world, in countries throughout Europe, and also the United States, Australia, Russia, [[Brazil]], Japan, [[Malaysia]], [[Taiwan]] and [[South Korea]]. She has also sung opera and pop classics with [[Bryan Ferry]], [[Eurythmics]] and [[Mick Hucknall]] to celebrate the arrival of the new century on Millennium Eve in the grounds at the [[Royal Observatory, Greenwich|Royal Observatory]] and [[National Maritime Museum]].<ref name=\"Lesley Garrett on Classic FM\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.classicfm.com/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061022050621/http://www.classicfm.com/article.asp?id=209974|url-status=dead|title=ClassicFM.com|archivedate=22 October 2006|website=Classic FM}}</ref>\n\nShe played the lead role of Hanna Glawari in the [[Welsh National Opera]]'s production of ''[[The Merry Widow]]'', which toured the United Kingdom in 2005. In 2006 she sang the role of Mother Abbess in [[Andrew Lloyd Webber]]'s revival of ''[[The Sound of Music#2006 London revival|The Sound of Music]]''. In 2008, she joined the cast of ''[[Carousel (musical)|Carousel]]'' as Nettie Fowler. The production toured the UK and then transferred to the West End's [[Savoy Theatre]]. In 2013 she returned to opera with the [[monodrama]] ''[[La Voix humaine]]'' for [[Opera North]].\n\nShe created the role of Val in ''Pleasure'', the first opera by [[Mark Simpson (clarinetist)|Mark Simpson]], directed by [[Tim Albery]] and premiered at the Howard Assembly Room by Opera North, in April 2016.<ref>Martin Dreyer. Report from Leeds. ''[[Opera (magazine)|Opera]]'', July 2016, Vol 67 No. 7, p895-897.</ref>\n\nGarrett is a member of the board of the [[English National Opera]] and a vice president of [[Harrogate International Festivals]].\n\nIn 2002 Garrett was appointed a [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] for her services to music. She was also awarded with a [[BASCA]] Gold Badge Award in October 2010, in recognition of her contribution to music.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/1198863/gold-badges-for-heather-small-john-paul-jones |title=Gold Badges For Heather Small, John Paul Jones |website=Billboard}}</ref>\n\n===Performances at sporting events===\nGarrett has performed at several [[FA Cup Final]]s, including the [[2000 FA Cup Final|2000 Final]], the last to be held at the old [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]],<ref name=bbc/> the [[2007 FA Cup Final|2007 final]] held at the new [[Wembley Stadium]] (alongside [[Sarah Brightman]]), and the [[2008 FA Cup Final|2008 Final]] (alongside [[Katherine Jenkins]]).\n\nShe also sang [[God Save the Queen|the British national anthem]] on the [[Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es]] in Paris in 2012 after [[Bradley Wiggins]] became the first Briton to win the [[Tour de France]], though her performance was not universally appreciated.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lesley Garrett's ghastly rendition of the National Anthem at Tour de France ceremony |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/9420290/Lesley-Garretts-ghastly-rendition-of-the-National-Anthem-at-Tour-de-France-ceremony.html |first=Rupert |last=Christiansen |authorlink=Rupert Christiansen |date=23 July 2012 |newspaper=[[The Telegraph (UK)|The Telegraph]]}}</ref>\n\n==Television and radio==\nIn 2004, Garrett was one of the participants in the first series of the celebrity talent contest ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]''; she and her dance partner [[Anton du Beke]] finished third. In the same year she took part in the BBC's ''[[Who Do You Think You Are? (UK TV series)|Who Do You Think You Are?]]'', a [[genealogy]] documentary series, in which she journeyed through her home town of [[Thorne, South Yorkshire|Thorne]] in search of her family history. She was delighted to discover that the musical gene stretched far back and had run in her family for several generations.<ref name=\"wdytya LG\">{{cite episode |title=Who Do You Think You Are? with Lesley Garrett |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/history/familyhistory/get_started/wdytya_s1_celeb_gallery_08.shtml\n|series=Who Do You Think You Are? |serieslink=Who Do You Think You Are? (British TV series) |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC Two]] |airdate=2004-11-30}}</ref> Garrett is a veteran of Dictionary Corner on the [[Channel 4]] game show ''[[Countdown (game show)|Countdown]]'', and in June 2005 it was thought that she was to become one of the show's rotating guest hosts while [[Richard Whiteley]] was recovering from illness. After Whiteley's death, however, the plan for rotating guest hosts was abandoned and [[Des Lynam]] took the role for the next fifteen months. Garrett did not appear on Countdown again until October 2009.\n\nOn Christmas Day 2004, [[BBC Two]] broadcast ''Lesley Garrett \u2013 Music from the Movies'', co-starring her with [[Ruthie Henshall]], [[Michael McCarthy (singer)|Michael McCarthy]] with the backing of the [[Opera North]] orchestra.<ref name=Christmas_2004>{{cite web |title=Lesley Garrett \u2013 Music from the Movies |year=2004 |last1=Garrett |first1=Lesley |last2=Henshall |first2=Ruthie |last3=McCarthy |first3=Michael |author-link2=Ruthie Henshall |author-link3=Michael McCarthy (singer) |publisher=[[BBC Two]] |accessdate=18 April 2015 |url=http://ukchristmastv.weebly.com/bbc-2004.html}}</ref> The programme was recorded at the ''Opera In The Park'' concert which had taken place in the grounds of [[Temple Newsam]], West Yorkshire on 19 July 2003.<ref name=Garrett>{{cite AV media notes |title=Lesley Garrett \u2013 Music from the Movies |year=2004 |last1=McCarthy |first1=Michael |last2=Garrett |first2=Lesley |last3=Henshall |first3=Ruthie |author-link2=Lesley Garrett |author-link3=Ruthie Henshall |publisher=[[Eagle Rock Entertainment]] |asin=B000HN328M |id=Barcode: 5036369804497 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150418171657/http://www.eagle-rock.com/product/music-from-the-movies/ |archive-date=18 April 2015 |url= http://www.eagle-rock.com/product/music-from-the-movies/#.VS265L-ME7A}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2005, Garrett was selected to be one of the judges for BBC's ''[[Comic Relief does Fame Academy]]'', and in May she hosted and sang at the 2005 [[Classical BRIT Awards]] at the [[Royal Albert Hall]] on ITV. She was a regular panellist on the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] [[daytime television|daytime show]] ''[[Loose Women]]'' during 2006; she featured there again in 2009 and 2010, before returning in May 2014. Garrett also appeared on ''[[This Morning (TV programme)|This Morning]]'' and ''Loose Women'' in 2007, to perform a song from her latest album ''When I Fall in Love''. She also continued the post as a judge on ''Comic Relief Does Fame Academy'' in 2007.<ref>[http://www.thestage.co.uk/podcasts/2007/02/lesley_garrett_podcast_transcript.php ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070313211351/http://www.thestage.co.uk/podcasts/2007/02/lesley_garrett_podcast_transcript.php |date=13 March 2007}}</ref> She currently presents a show on the British [[European classical music|classical]] radio station [[Classic FM (UK)|Classic FM]].\n\nFrom February 2008 Garrett presented the show ''Lesley Garrett's 20 Operas to See Before You Die'' on ''[[Sky Arts]]''.<ref>[http://www.skyarts.co.uk/SkyArts/Opera/Article.aspx?artid=5315]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080219224923/http://www.skyarts.co.uk/SkyArts/Opera/Article.aspx?artid=5315 |date=19 February 2008 }}</ref>\n\nOver four weeks, beginning on 30 November 2008, she presented the Sunday morning BBC1 programme ''Christmas Voices''.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/religion/programmes/advent/christmasvoices.shtml] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071230035615/http://www.bbc.co.uk/religion/programmes/advent/christmasvoices.shtml |date=30 December 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2010 she joined a long line of panellists on Five's ''[[The Wright Stuff]]''.\n\nAlong with [[Larry Lamb (actor)|Larry Lamb]], Garrett presented a short BBC series entitled ''When Royals Wed'' to celebrate the [[wedding of Prince William and Catherine Middleton]] in April 2011.\n\nOn 30 May 2014 she made her return to the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] [[daytime television|daytime show]] ''[[Loose Women]]''. It was announced on the programme that she would become a regular panellist again.\n\nShe featured on the TV show ''My Life on a Plate'' on 10 September 2017; chef [[Brian Turner (chef)|Brian Turner]] accompanied her on a trip to key locations from her childhood in Yorkshire, where she was taught by her parents to make the most out of what was available. The chef then created two dishes that wove nostalgia and the taste of home together.\n\n==Personal life==\nGarrett married in May 1991: her husband Peter<ref>{{cite news |author= |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/personalfinance/fameandfortune/4798651/Fame-and-Fortune-Opera-singer-Lesley-Garrett.html |title=Fame & Fortune: Opera singer Lesley Garrett |publisher=Telegraph |date=24 February 2009 |accessdate=14 May 2012}}</ref> is a [[General practitioner|GP]] in [[Muswell Hill]]. They have a son, Jeremy, and a daughter, Chloe. The family lives in [[north London]].\n\nGarrett featured in an episode of the BBC's popular genealogy programme, ''[[Who Do You Think You Are? (UK TV series)|Who Do You Think You Are?]]'', in which she explored her family's Yorkshire origins. She found out about the musicians in her family: her maternal grandfather made a living playing the piano with a small orchestra that accompanied silent films at cinemas in and around [[Sheffield]]. A great-grandfather was a travelling musician, working across [[northern England]] in the 19th century, playing to workers in pubs and clubs. During the [[First World War]] he entertained troops on the piano.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/whodoyouthinkyouare/past-stories/lesley-garrett.shtml |title=Who Do You Think You Are? |publisher=BBC |accessdate=7 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\nAs a recording artist, Garrett has released eleven solo albums. Many of them have been successful, receiving gold and silver status. ''Soprano in Red'' received the [[Gramophone Award]] for \"Best-selling Classical Artist of the Year\". Garrett was also a featured artist on the platinum selling \"[[Perfect Day (Lou Reed song)|Perfect Day]]\" single released by the [[BBC]] in aid of [[Children in Need]].<ref name=\"Lesley Garrett on Classic FM\"/>\n\nGarrett created the role of Cathy in the London studio recording of [[Bernard J. Taylor]]'s operatic version of ''[[Wuthering Heights]]'', which also featured [[Dave Willetts]], [[Bonnie Langford]] and other leading British musical theatre performers. Her rendition of \"I Belong to the Earth\" was included on two of her solo albums.\n\nOther recordings include complete audio operas: Mozart's ''The Magic Flute'' (Papagena) conducted by [[Sir Charles Mackerras]], Mozart's ''Cos\u00ec fan tutte'' (Despina), also conducted by Mackerras and Yum-Yum in the audio and video recordings of the [[Jonathan Miller]] production of ''[[The Mikado]]'' from ENO, in which she played the leading soprano role, Yum-Yum. She appears on two other DVDs of complete works from English National Opera, Handel's ''Ariodante'' (Dalinda) and ''[[Xerxes (opera)|Xerxes]]'' (Atalanta). In the video of the 1984 [[Glyndebourne Festival Opera|Glyndebourne]] ''[[L'incoronazione di Poppea discography|L'incoronazione di Poppea]]'' under [[Raymond Leppard]], she sings Nutrice and Valletto.\n\n===Solo albums===\n;Studio<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book\n| first= David\n| last= Roberts\n| year= 2006\n| title= British Hit Singles & Albums\n| edition= 19th\n| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited\n| location= London\n| isbn= 1-904994-10-5\n| page= 222}}</ref>\n*''A Soprano at the Movies'' (1991)\n*''Prima Donna'' (1992)\n*''Simple Gifts'' (1994)\n*''The Lesley Garrett Album'' (1994) \u2013 [[UK Albums Chart|UK]] No. 25\n*''Soprano in Red'' (1995) \u2013 No. 59\n*''Soprano in Hollywood'' (1996) \u2013 UK No. 53\n*''A Soprano Inspired'' (1997) \u2013 UK No. 48\n*''Lesley Garrett'' (1998) \u2013 UK No. 34\n*''I Will Wait For You'' (2000) \u2013 UK No. 28\n*''[[Travelling Light (Lesley Garrett album)|Travelling Light]]'' (2001) \u2013 UK No. 75\n*''The Singer'' (2002)\n*''So Deep is the Night'' (2003)\n*''When I Fall in Love'' (2007) \u2013 UK No. 11\n*''Amazing Grace'' (2008) \u2013 UK No. 50\n*''A North Country Lass'' (2012) \u2013 UK No. 66\n*''Centre Stage: The Musicals Album'' (2015)\n\n====Compilation albums====\n*''The Soprano's Greatest Hits'' (1997) \u2013 UK No. 53\n*''The Best of Lesley Garrett'' (2004)\n\n===Solo DVDs===\n*''Lesley Garrett'' (1998)\n*''I Will Wait For You'' (2000)\n*''Notes From The Heart'' (2003)\n*''Desert Dreams'' (2004)\n*''Lesley Garrett: Music from the Movies'' (2006)\n*''Lesley Garrett Live At Christmas'' (2008)\n\n==Bibliography==\n*''Notes From a Small Soprano'' \u2013 2000\n*''Lesley Garrett: My Autobiography''* \u2013 2000\n*''Lesley Garrett Song Collection'' \u2013 2001\n\n<small>* Reprint of ''Notes From a Small Soprano'' with few edits. Also the title of some copies of the audiobook.</small>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.lesleygarrett.co.uk Lesley Garrett's Official Website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090324012227/http://www.classicsandjazz.co.uk/plink/Lesley+Garrett Official Record Label Website ]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070713202147/http://www.classicalx.com/Lesley_Garrett.html Lesley Garrett's section on ClassicalX]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070202022154/http://www.theatre.com/ask_a_star/id/3004458 2006 article on Lesley Garrett on Theatre.com]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061022044026/http://www.classicfm.com/sectional.asp?id=9432 Lesley Garrett's page on ''Classic FM'']\n*{{IMDb name|id=0308162|name=Lesley Garrett}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Garrett, Lesley}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal Academy of Music]]\n[[Category:Classical music radio presenters]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:English female singers]]\n[[Category:English sopranos]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) people]]\n[[Category:People from Thorne, South Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:People from Muswell Hill]]\n[[Category:People educated at Thorne Grammar School]]\n[[Category:Women radio presenters]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name           = Lesley Garrett<br><small>[[Order of the British Empire|CBE]]</small>\n| alias          = \n| background     = solo_singer\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| birth_name     = \n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1955|4|10}}\n| birth_place    = [[Thorne, South Yorkshire|Thorne]], [[Doncaster]], [[South Yorkshire]], England\n| occupation     = {{hlist|Singer\u2013songwriter|musician|broadcaster|[[Infotainment|media personality]]}}\n| genre          = Classical, [[crossover music|classical-crossover]]\n| years_active   = 1979\u2013present\n| label          = [[Decca Records|Decca]]<br>[[Universal Classics and Jazz]]<br>[[Universal Music International]]\n| website        = [http://www.lesleygarrett.co.uk/ Official site]\n}}\n\n'''Lesley Garrett''', [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] (born 10 April 1955) is an English [[soprano singer]], musician, broadcaster and media personality.  She is noted for being at home in opera and \"[[crossover music]]\".<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/1734956.stm |title=UK &#124; Lesley Garrett: Doncaster's own diva |publisher=BBC News |date=31 December 2001 |accessdate=10 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nGarrett was born in the town of [[Thorne, South Yorkshire|Thorne]], near Doncaster, South Yorkshire into a musical family. She attended Thorne Fieldside Infant and Junior Schools and [[Thorne Grammar School]], where she performed in school plays and musicals and passed 10 [[GCE Ordinary Level|O-levels]] and an [[GCE Advanced Level|A-level]] in music.<ref>''[[Daily Mail]]'' Weekend Interview. 12 May 2012, p6</ref> As she grew up she inherited her family's love of music. Her grandfather Colin Wall was a classical pianist; her father Derek worked as a railway signalman and then as a schoolteacher at Hatfield Woodhouse Primary School, eventually going on to become a headmaster. They lived nearby just south of the village; her mother Margaret (n\u00e9e Wall) was a talented singing seamstress and became the school secretary at Lesley's primary school. She has two sisters, Jill and Kay, one step-sister, Louise, and two step-brothers named Robert and Nicholas. When Lesley was 17 she washed dishes at the officers' mess at nearby [[RAF Lindholme]] as a summer job.<ref name=\"Dishes\">{{cite web|author=Liz Phillips |url=http://www.thisismoney.co.uk/celebrity/article.html?in_article_id=421297&in_page_id=181 |title=Lesley Garrett: My money |publisher=This is Money |date=13 June 2007 |accessdate=10 August 2014}}</ref> While a student at the [[Royal Academy of Music]] she worked as a life model, something of which she is still proud.<ref>{{cite web |last=Paton |first=Maureen |url=http://mygetupandgo.co.uk/2012/06/this-life-lesley-garrett/ |title=This LIfe, Lesley Garrett &#124; Get up and go |publisher=Mygetupandgo.co.uk |date=3 June 2012 |accessdate=10 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140730151143/http://mygetupandgo.co.uk/2012/06/this-life-lesley-garrett/ |archivedate=30 July 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Music==\nGarrett has had an extensive music career. A graduate of the [[Royal Academy of Music]] and an alumna of the prestigious [[National Opera Studio]], she won the Decca Prize of the [[Kathleen Ferrier Award]] in 1979, thereby launching her career.<ref>{{cite web\n|url = http://www.ferrierawards.org.uk/main/winners.asp\n|title = The Kathleen Ferrier Awards \u2013 Winners\n|accessdate = 6 March 2008}}</ref> Her professional debut, in 1979, was as Amor in ''[[Orontea]]'' at the music festival in [[Batignano]]. She subsequently sang, in 1980, Alice in ''[[Le comte Ory]]'' at the [[London Coliseum]] and Dorinda in ''[[Orlando (opera)|Orlando]]'' at the [[Wexford Festival]], in 1981, also at Wexford, the title role in ''[[Zaide]]'', in 1982 Sophie in ''[[Werther]]'' with [[Opera North]] and in 1984 Damigella in ''[[L'incoronazione di Poppea]]'' at [[Glyndebourne Festival Opera|Glyndebourne]].<ref>{{cite book| last = Adam| first = Nicky (ed)| year = 1993| title = Who's Who in British Opera| publisher = Scolar Press| location = Aldershot| page = [https://archive.org/details/whoswhoinbritish0000adam/page/98 98]| isbn = 0-859-67894-6| url = https://archive.org/details/whoswhoinbritish0000adam/page/98}}</ref> From 1984, as principal soprano at [[English National Opera]], she became well known for her performances in productions of the operas ''[[Serse]]'', ''[[The Marriage of Figaro|Le Nozze di Figaro]]'', ''[[Cos\u00ec fan tutte]]'' ''[[Die Fledermaus]]''<ref name=\"bbc\" /> and ''[[The Mikado]]''.<ref>Rahim, Sameer. [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/opera/9841816/The-opera-novice-The-Mikado-by-Gilbert-and-Sullivan.html \"The opera novice: ''The Mikado'' by Gilbert & Sullivan\"], ''The Telegraph'', 1 February 2013</ref>\n\nGarrett has performed across the world, in countries throughout Europe, and also the United States, Australia, Russia, [[Brazil]], Japan, [[Malaysia]], [[Taiwan]] and [[South Korea]]. She has also sung opera and pop classics with [[Bryan Ferry]], [[Eurythmics]] and [[Mick Hucknall]] to celebrate the arrival of the new century on Millennium Eve in the grounds at the [[Royal Observatory, Greenwich|Royal Observatory]] and [[National Maritime Museum]].<ref name=\"Lesley Garrett on Classic FM\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.classicfm.com/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061022050621/http://www.classicfm.com/article.asp?id=209974|url-status=dead|title=ClassicFM.com|archivedate=22 October 2006|website=Classic FM}}</ref>\n\nShe played the lead role of Hanna Glawari in the [[Welsh National Opera]]'s production of ''[[The Merry Widow]]'', which toured the United Kingdom in 2005. In 2006 she sang the role of Mother Abbess in [[Andrew Lloyd Webber]]'s revival of ''[[The Sound of Music#2006 London revival|The Sound of Music]]''. In 2008, she joined the cast of ''[[Carousel (musical)|Carousel]]'' as Nettie Fowler. The production toured the UK and then transferred to the West End's [[Savoy Theatre]]. In 2013 she returned to opera with the [[monodrama]] ''[[La Voix humaine]]'' for [[Opera North]].\n\nShe created the role of Val in ''Pleasure'', the first opera by [[Mark Simpson (clarinetist)|Mark Simpson]], directed by [[Tim Albery]] and premiered at the Howard Assembly Room by Opera North, in April 2016.<ref>Martin Dreyer. Report from Leeds. ''[[Opera (magazine)|Opera]]'', July 2016, Vol 67 No. 7, p895-897.</ref>\n\nGarrett is a member of the board of the [[English National Opera]] and a vice president of [[Harrogate International Festivals]].\n\nIn 2002 Garrett was appointed a [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] for her services to music. She was also awarded with a [[BASCA]] Gold Badge Award in October 2010, in recognition of her contribution to music.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/1198863/gold-badges-for-heather-small-john-paul-jones |title=Gold Badges For Heather Small, John Paul Jones |website=Billboard}}</ref>\n\n===Performances at sporting events===\nGarrett has performed at several [[FA Cup Final]]s, including the [[2000 FA Cup Final|2000 Final]], the last to be held at the old [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]],<ref name=bbc/> the [[2007 FA Cup Final|2007 final]] held at the new [[Wembley Stadium]] (alongside [[Sarah Brightman]]), and the [[2008 FA Cup Final|2008 Final]] (alongside [[Katherine Jenkins]]).\n\nShe also sang [[God Save the Queen|the British national anthem]] on the [[Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es]] in Paris in 2012 after [[Bradley Wiggins]] became the first Briton to win the [[Tour de France]], though her performance was not universally appreciated.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lesley Garrett's ghastly rendition of the National Anthem at Tour de France ceremony |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/9420290/Lesley-Garretts-ghastly-rendition-of-the-National-Anthem-at-Tour-de-France-ceremony.html |first=Rupert |last=Christiansen |authorlink=Rupert Christiansen |date=23 July 2012 |newspaper=[[The Telegraph (UK)|The Telegraph]]}}</ref>\n\n==Television and radio==\nIn 2004, Garrett was one of the participants in the first series of the celebrity talent contest ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]''; she and her dance partner [[Anton du Beke]] finished third. In the same year she took part in the BBC's ''[[Who Do You Think You Are? (UK TV series)|Who Do You Think You Are?]]'', a [[genealogy]] documentary series, in which she journeyed through her home town of [[Thorne, South Yorkshire|Thorne]] in search of her family history. She was delighted to discover that the musical gene stretched far back and had run in her family for several generations.<ref name=\"wdytya LG\">{{cite episode |title=Who Do You Think You Are? with Lesley Garrett |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/history/familyhistory/get_started/wdytya_s1_celeb_gallery_08.shtml\n|series=Who Do You Think You Are? |serieslink=Who Do You Think You Are? (British TV series) |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC Two]] |airdate=2004-11-30}}</ref> Garrett is a veteran of Dictionary Corner on the [[Channel 4]] game show ''[[Countdown (game show)|Countdown]]'', and in June 2005 it was thought that she was to become one of the show's rotating guest hosts while [[Richard Whiteley]] was recovering from illness. After Whiteley's death, however, the plan for rotating guest hosts was abandoned and [[Des Lynam]] took the role for the next fifteen months. Garrett did not appear on Countdown again until October 2009.\n\nOn Christmas Day 2004, [[BBC Two]] broadcast ''Lesley Garrett \u2013 Music from the Movies'', co-starring her with [[Ruthie Henshall]], [[Michael McCarthy (singer)|Michael McCarthy]] with the backing of the [[Opera North]] orchestra.<ref name=Christmas_2004>{{cite web |title=Lesley Garrett \u2013 Music from the Movies |year=2004 |last1=Garrett |first1=Lesley |last2=Henshall |first2=Ruthie |last3=McCarthy |first3=Michael |author-link2=Ruthie Henshall |author-link3=Michael McCarthy (singer) |publisher=[[BBC Two]] |accessdate=18 April 2015 |url=http://ukchristmastv.weebly.com/bbc-2004.html}}</ref> The programme was recorded at the ''Opera In The Park'' concert which had taken place in the grounds of [[Temple Newsam]], West Yorkshire on 19 July 2003.<ref name=Garrett>{{cite AV media notes |title=Lesley Garrett \u2013 Music from the Movies |year=2004 |last1=McCarthy |first1=Michael |last2=Garrett |first2=Lesley |last3=Henshall |first3=Ruthie |author-link2=Lesley Garrett |author-link3=Ruthie Henshall |publisher=[[Eagle Rock Entertainment]] |asin=B000HN328M |id=Barcode: 5036369804497 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150418171657/http://www.eagle-rock.com/product/music-from-the-movies/ |archive-date=18 April 2015 |url= http://www.eagle-rock.com/product/music-from-the-movies/#.VS265L-ME7A}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2005, Garrett was selected to be one of the judges for BBC's ''[[Comic Relief does Fame Academy]]'', and in May she hosted and sang at the 2005 [[Classical BRIT Awards]] at the [[Royal Albert Hall]] on ITV. She was a regular panellist on the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] [[daytime television|daytime show]] ''[[Loose Women]]'' during 2006; she featured there again in 2009 and 2010, before returning in May 2014. Garrett also appeared on ''[[This Morning (TV programme)|This Morning]]'' and ''Loose Women'' in 2007, to perform a song from her latest album ''When I Fall in Love''. She also continued the post as a judge on ''Comic Relief Does Fame Academy'' in 2007.<ref>[http://www.thestage.co.uk/podcasts/2007/02/lesley_garrett_podcast_transcript.php ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070313211351/http://www.thestage.co.uk/podcasts/2007/02/lesley_garrett_podcast_transcript.php |date=13 March 2007}}</ref> She currently presents a show on the British [[European classical music|classical]] radio station [[Classic FM (UK)|Classic FM]].\n\nFrom February 2008 Garrett presented the show ''Lesley Garrett's 20 Operas to See Before You Die'' on ''[[Sky Arts]]''.<ref>[http://www.skyarts.co.uk/SkyArts/Opera/Article.aspx?artid=5315]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080219224923/http://www.skyarts.co.uk/SkyArts/Opera/Article.aspx?artid=5315 |date=19 February 2008 }}</ref>\n\nOver four weeks, beginning on 30 November 2008, she presented the Sunday morning BBC1 programme ''Christmas Voices''.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/religion/programmes/advent/christmasvoices.shtml] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071230035615/http://www.bbc.co.uk/religion/programmes/advent/christmasvoices.shtml |date=30 December 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2010 she joined a long line of panellists on Five's ''[[The Wright Stuff]]''.\n\nAlong with [[Larry Lamb (actor)|Larry Lamb]], Garrett presented a short BBC series entitled ''When Royals Wed'' to celebrate the [[wedding of Prince William and Catherine Middleton]] in April 2011.\n\nOn 30 May 2014 she made her return to the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] [[daytime television|daytime show]] ''[[Loose Women]]''. It was announced on the programme that she would become a regular panellist again.\n\nShe featured on the TV show ''My Life on a Plate'' on 10 September 2017; chef [[Brian Turner (chef)|Brian Turner]] accompanied her on a trip to key locations from her childhood in Yorkshire, where she was taught by her parents to make the most out of what was available. The chef then created two dishes that wove nostalgia and the taste of home together.\n\n==Personal life==\nGarrett married in May 1991: her husband Peter<ref>{{cite news |author= |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/personalfinance/fameandfortune/4798651/Fame-and-Fortune-Opera-singer-Lesley-Garrett.html |title=Fame & Fortune: Opera singer Lesley Garrett |publisher=Telegraph |date=24 February 2009 |accessdate=14 May 2012}}</ref> is a [[General practitioner|GP]] in [[Muswell Hill]]. They have a son, Jeremy, and a daughter, Chloe. The family lives in [[north London]].\n\nGarrett featured in an episode of the BBC's popular genealogy programme, ''[[Who Do You Think You Are? (UK TV series)|Who Do You Think You Are?]]'', in which she explored her family's Yorkshire origins. She found out about the musicians in her family: her maternal grandfather made a living playing the piano with a small orchestra that accompanied silent films at cinemas in and around [[Sheffield]]. A great-grandfather was a travelling musician, working across [[northern England]] in the 19th century, playing to workers in pubs and clubs. During the [[First World War]] he entertained troops on the piano.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/whodoyouthinkyouare/past-stories/lesley-garrett.shtml |title=Who Do You Think You Are? |publisher=BBC |accessdate=7 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\nAs a recording artist, Garrett has released eleven solo albums. Many of them have been successful, receiving gold and silver status. ''Soprano in Red'' received the [[Gramophone Award]] for \"Best-selling Classical Artist of the Year\". Garrett was also a featured artist on the platinum selling \"[[Perfect Day (Lou Reed song)|Perfect Day]]\" single released by the [[BBC]] in aid of [[Children in Need]].<ref name=\"Lesley Garrett on Classic FM\"/>\n\nGarrett created the role of Cathy in the London studio recording of [[Bernard J. Taylor]]'s operatic version of ''[[Wuthering Heights]]'', which also featured [[Dave Willetts]], [[Bonnie Langford]] and other leading singers from the British musical stage. Her rendition of \"I Belong to the Earth\" was included on two of her solo albums.\n\nOther recordings include complete audio operas: Mozart's ''The Magic Flute'' (Papagena) conducted by [[Sir Charles Mackerras]], Mozart's ''Cos\u00ec fan tutte'' (Despina), also conducted by Mackerras and Yum-Yum in the audio and video recordings of the [[Jonathan Miller]] production of ''[[The Mikado]]'' from ENO, in which she played the leading soprano role, Yum-Yum. She appears on two other DVDs of complete works from English National Opera, Handel's ''Ariodante'' (Dalinda) and ''[[Xerxes (opera)|Xerxes]]'' (Atalanta). In the video of the 1984 [[Glyndebourne Festival Opera|Glyndebourne]] ''[[L'incoronazione di Poppea discography|L'incoronazione di Poppea]]'' under [[Raymond Leppard]], she sings Nutrice and Valletto.\n\n===Solo albums===\n;Studio<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book\n| first= David\n| last= Roberts\n| year= 2006\n| title= British Hit Singles & Albums\n| edition= 19th\n| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited\n| location= London\n| isbn= 1-904994-10-5\n| page= 222}}</ref>\n*''A Soprano at the Movies'' (1991)\n*''Prima Donna'' (1992)\n*''Simple Gifts'' (1994)\n*''The Lesley Garrett Album'' (1994) \u2013 [[UK Albums Chart|UK]] No. 25\n*''Soprano in Red'' (1995) \u2013 No. 59\n*''Soprano in Hollywood'' (1996) \u2013 UK No. 53\n*''A Soprano Inspired'' (1997) \u2013 UK No. 48\n*''Lesley Garrett'' (1998) \u2013 UK No. 34\n*''I Will Wait For You'' (2000) \u2013 UK No. 28\n*''[[Travelling Light (Lesley Garrett album)|Travelling Light]]'' (2001) \u2013 UK No. 75\n*''The Singer'' (2002)\n*''So Deep is the Night'' (2003)\n*''When I Fall in Love'' (2007) \u2013 UK No. 11\n*''Amazing Grace (Lesley Garrett album)'' (2008) \u2013 UK No. 50\n*''A North Country Lass'' (2012) \u2013 UK No. 66\n*''Centre Stage: The Musicals Album'' (2015)\n\n====Compilation albums====\n*''The Soprano's Greatest Hits'' (1997) \u2013 UK No. 53\n*''The Best of Lesley Garrett'' (2004)\n\n===Solo DVDs===\n*''Lesley Garrett'' (1998)\n*''I Will Wait For You'' (2000)\n*''Notes From The Heart'' (2003)\n*''Desert Dreams'' (2004)\n*''Lesley Garrett: Music from the Movies'' (2006)\n*''Lesley Garrett Live At Christmas'' (2008)\n\n==Bibliography==\n*''Notes From a Small Soprano'' \u2013 2000\n*''Lesley Garrett: My Autobiography''* \u2013 2000\n*''Lesley Garrett Song Collection'' \u2013 2001\n\n<small>* Reprint of ''Notes From a Small Soprano'' with few edits. Also the title of some copies of the audiobook.</small>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.lesleygarrett.co.uk Lesley Garrett's Official Website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090324012227/http://www.classicsandjazz.co.uk/plink/Lesley+Garrett Official Record Label Website ]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070713202147/http://www.classicalx.com/Lesley_Garrett.html Lesley Garrett's section on ClassicalX]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070202022154/http://www.theatre.com/ask_a_star/id/3004458 20